TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_TEXT
John and Brian each live 2 kilometers from their school.  John walks to school and Brian rides his bicycle.  The graphs show the distance each boy travels to school.
$BR
\{ image( insertGraph($graph), tex_size=>$TEXSIZE,
    height=>$HEIGHT, width=>$WIDTH
    ) \}
$PAR
a) John walks \{ans_rule(3 )\}kilometers between minutes 3 and 8. $PAR


b) Brian is riding his bicycle at a speed of \{ans_rule(3 )\} kilometers per minute between minutes 11 and 15.$PAR

c)  
John and Brian travel at the same speed between minutes \{ans_rule(1 )\} and  \{ans_rule(1 )\}.$PAR

d) Maya walks at a constant rate of .1 km per min to school. If her walk to school is $maya_walk_school minutes, how many kilometers does she live from school? $SPACE \{ ans_rule(3) \}



END_TEXT
ANS(Real(0.4)->cmp);
ANS(Real(0)->cmp);
ANS(Real(6)->cmp);
ANS(Real(10)->cmp);
$ans_d = Compute($maya_walk_school * .1);
ANS($ans_d->cmp);
BEGIN_SOLUTION
$PAR Solution $PAR
a) At minute 3, John has walked 0.2 kilometers.  At minute 8, John has walked 0.6 kilometers. So, between minutes 3 and 8, John has walked 0.6-0.2=0.4 kilometers

$BR
b) Between minutes 11 and 15, Brian must have stopped since his distance at both times was 1.4 kilometers.  So his rate of speed was 0 kilometers per minute.
$BR
c) Between minutes 6 and 10 (when the red and green graphs are parallel) both 
$BR traveled at the same speed.
$BR
d) We know we need our answer to have distance units (km).  Therefore it makes sense to multiply Maya's speed by the time it took her to get to school.  Thus $maya_walk_school minutes * .1 km/min = $ans_d km
END_SOLUTION

